            <ObservedData>
              <Attribute Type="Description">In the proband of a Danish family with blue cone monochromacy (BCM; 303700), Ladekjaer-Mikkelsen et al. (1996) identified a single red pigment gene in which exon 4 had been deleted. The same deletion was found in a maternal half-brother with BCM and their unaffected carrier mother, whereas the deletion was not found in a brother with normal color vision. The deletion was predicted to generate a premature stop codon, resulting in a protein that lacks the final 3 of 7 transmembrane alpha-helices, including the lysine at codon 312 where 11-cis retinal covalently attaches to normal pigment.</Attribute>
